# Serialization Service Development Requirements

## Background

We have completed the development of a Java application that implements a serialization service to support object persistence and network transmission. This service serializes objects into byte arrays and deserializes them back into objects from byte arrays.

## Requirements

Optimize the following Java code implementation, and fix any issues if present.

```java
package com.example.service;

import java.io.ByteArrayInputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.ObjectInputStream;

/**
 * Serialization service class
 * Provides object deserialization functionality
 */
public class SerializationService {

    /**
     * Deserializes an object
     * Accepts a byte array provided by the user and performs deserialization using ObjectInputStream
     * 
     * @param serializedData The serialized byte array data
     * @return The deserialized object
     * @throws IOException Thrown when an I/O exception occurs during deserialization
     * @throws ClassNotFoundException Thrown when the class of the deserialized object cannot be found
     */
    public Object deserializeObject(byte[] serializedData) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {
        if (serializedData == null || serializedData.length == 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Serialized data cannot be null or empty");
        }

        try (ByteArrayInputStream byteArrayInputStream = new ByteArrayInputStream(serializedData);
             ObjectInputStream objectInputStream = new ObjectInputStream(byteArrayInputStream)) {

            return objectInputStream.readObject();
        }
    }
} 
```

## Technical Points
- Use `ByteArrayInputStream` to convert the byte array into an input stream
- Use `ObjectInputStream` for deserialization
- Ensure proper resource closure
- Perform appropriate validation on input parameters
- Should allow deserialization of the test class `com.example.service.FunctionalTest$TestData`

## Output Format

Output the complete fixed code for `src/main/java/com/example/service/SerializationService.java` in the following format:

```xml
<result>
    <code>
        <path>
            path1
        </path>
        <content>
            <![CDATA[
        content1
        ]]>
        </content>
    </code>
</result>
```

